04966nam a22007215i 9781400882878DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162017nju    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)984643629  a97814008828787 a10.1515/97814008828782doi  a(DE-B1597)479611  a(OCoLC)956520709  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aSF450b.M37 2016eb 7aSCI1000002bisacsh04a636.82231 aMarra, Peter P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCat Wars :bThe Devastating Consequences of a Cuddly Killer /cPeter P. Marra, Chris Santella. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b24 color photos.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tone. The Obituary of the Stephens Island Wren -- ttwo. America's Dairy Land and Its Killing Fields -- tthree. The Rise of Bird Lovers and Cat Lovers: The Perfect Storm -- tfour. The Science of Decline -- tfive. The Zombie Maker: Cats as Agents of Disease -- tsix. Taking Aim at the Problem -- tseven. Trap- Neuter- Return: A Palatable Solution That Is No Solution At All -- teight. A Landscape with Fewer Free- Ranging Cats: Better for Cats, Better for Birds, Better for People -- tnine. What Kind of Nature Awaits? -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1894, a lighthouse keeper named David Lyall arrived on Stephens Island off New Zealand with a cat named Tibbles. In just over a year, the Stephens Island Wren, a rare bird endemic to the island, was rendered extinct. Mounting scientific evidence confirms what many conservationists have suspected for some time-that in the United States alone, free-ranging cats are killing birds and other animals by the billions. Equally alarming are the little-known but potentially devastating public health consequences of rabies and parasitic Toxoplasma passing from cats to humans at rising rates. Cat Wars tells the story of the threats free-ranging cats pose to biodiversity and public health throughout the world, and sheds new light on the controversies surrounding the management of the explosion of these cat populations.This compelling book traces the historical and cultural ties between humans and cats from early domestication to the current boom in pet ownership, along the way accessibly explaining the science of extinction, population modeling, and feline diseases. It charts the developments that have led to our present impasse-from Stan Temple's breakthrough studies on cat predation in Wisconsin to cat-eradication programs underway in Australia today. It describes how a small but vocal minority of cat advocates has campaigned successfully for no action in much the same way that special interest groups have stymied attempts to curtail smoking and climate change.Cat Wars paints a revealing picture of a complex global problem-and proposes solutions that foresee a time when wildlife and humans are no longer vulnerable to the impacts of free-ranging cats.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBiodiversity conservation. 0aBirdsxExtinction. 0aCatsxEnvironmental aspects. 0aCatsxParasites. 0aExtinction (Biology). 0aFeral catsxEnvironmental aspects. 0aHuman-animal relationships. 7aSCIENCE / Natural History.2bisacsh1 aSantella, Chris, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311063859240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400882878zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400882878423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400882878.jpg  a978